post_text:
Great news! Effective Monday, September 14, all lunch meals will be available at NO CHARGE to all Southeast Dubois County students physically attending school. The USDA announced an emergency waiver which allows ALL students to receive a free breakfast and lunch each day at school. Due to limited breakfast supplies, we will begin offering free breakfast to all students on September 21.

The USDA waiver will be in effect until December 31, or until funds run out (whichever is first). Once the waiver or funds expire, breakfast and lunch will return to its normal price.

There will be no change to the menu or food items offered. Students may continue to purchase a la carte items at current pricing.

We are incredibly grateful for this support from the USDA. What a great benefit for all kids!!

post_text:
All Dubois County School Corporations, in collaboration with the Dubois County Health Department, have determined that the 2020-2021 school year will begin for all students on Wednesday, August 12, 2020. Students opting for in-person instruction should plan to be in attendance on campus. Increased safety precautions will be implemented in accordance with recommended reopening plan modifications. Modifications include daily screening of all students and staff prior to entering school facilities, the use of face coverings per order of the Governor and SED policy, and minimizing student contact where possible. All information pertaining to reopening school can be found at www.sedubois.k12.in.us under the Covid-19 tab.

Please keep your child home if they are ill, exhibiting symptoms of COVID-19 or are being tested or awaiting test results for COVID-19.

SED will continue to work closely with the Dubois County Health Department to monitor the situation. Any changes to our school status will be communicated promptly as they arise.

post_text:
Today, the DOE released a document designed to assist schools as they plan to re-open in August. As a reminder, all Dubois County School Districts will be working collaboratively to plan to safely and appropriately reopen school for the 2020-2021 school year.

There is an immense amount of guidance and information from the Governor's Office, Department of Education, and Health Department that we will use to form a flexible plan that we will use to re-open.

Each county is unique and the solution to starting school in the fall will be just as unique. We recognize our part in providing for a safe learning environment and serving as a vital partner in our local economy. More information will be forthcoming as we await work through the process and vet the various resources.

The Indiana General Assembly has approved a bill changing the enrollment date for kindergarten from August 1, 2019 to September 1, 2019.

Therefore, if your child will be five years of age on or before September 1, 2019, he or she will be eligible to enroll in kindergarten for the 2019-2020 school year.

We have already had our KG roundups, so to enroll for the 2019-20 school year contact one of our schools if your child meets the new eligibility requirements.

Pike Central Vocational Welding students swept the top five places at the Region 4 Skills USA Welding Contest held at Vincennes University on Saturday, February 2. Six Pike Central Vocational Welding students competed.

Forest Park senior Swayde Morgan placing first. Swayde received a $2,500 scholarship from Vincennes University.

Placing second was Pike Central senior Gage Cummings. Gage received a $1,000 scholarship from Vincennes University.

Placing third was Forest Park senior Nick Werner. Nick received a $500 scholarship from Vincennes University.

Placing fourth was Forest Park senior Elliott Wiseman. Elliott received a $500 scholarship from Vincennes University.

post_text: Congratulation to Forest Park High School Freshman Magda Alvis for having her artwork selected for the International Violin Competition of Indianapolis. Magda was one of five students who had their artwork selected by the International Violin Competition from Region 5. Artwork from Region 5 consisted of 18 counties in southwestern Indiana. Magda's will receive $25 and Certificate of Achievement at the Gala Awards Ceremony on May 6th at Indiana Landmarks in Indianapolis. Her artwork advanced to the finals where a total of 30 Grand Award Winners will be chosen from the five Regions throughout the state. More than 21,000 students participated throughout the state. Ms. Tammy Taylor is her art educator.

post_text:
All Dubois County School Corporations were notified by local law enforcement of a social media post that alluded to threats to school Veterans Day Programs. After investigation by local law enforcement, this threat was deemed not credible nor pertaining to Dubois County but a school corporation elsewhere. As a precautionary measure, we invited local law enforcement to increase their presence at scheduled Veterans Day programs at our schools.
We truly appreciate the commitment of all county law enforcement agencies in ensuring our students, staff and community members are safe as we pay tribute to the many who have served our great country.

post_text:
The Indiana Commission for Higher Education is pleased to announce the Next Generation Hoosier Educators Scholarship application opens September 1, 2017. The scholarship provides 200 high-achieving high school and college students interested in pursuing a career in education the opportunity to earn a renewable scholarship of up to $7,500 each year for four academic years. In exchange, students agree to teach for five years at an eligible Indiana school.

Students interested in applying must have a teacher complete a nomination form and upload the nomination form in their online application through ScholarTrack. Applications are due by 11:59 p.m. EST on November 30, 2017.

In exchange, students agree to teach for five years at an eligible Indiana school.

Students interested in applying must have a teacher complete a nomination form and upload the nomination form in their online application through ScholarTrack. Applications are due by 11:59 p.m. EST on November 30, 2017.

From our Band Boosters page: Wed., Dec. 21st, cast a vote for the FP Band Boosters and help them receive a $10,000 grant from the Dubois County Community Foundation.

Votes are cast in the form of writing a post that says "FP Band Boosters" on the DCCF Facebook page. 3.) A "like" or "me too" comment on someone else's post does not count as a vote. 4.) one vote per person.
Check the official rules once they are posted on the DCCF Facebook page and follow them if they differ from above. Let's see huge voter turnout for the FP Band Boosters!!

We are currently looking for interested folks to become bus drivers.

Requirements include:

*CDL License and Physical
*Pass Physical Performance Test
*3 Day Pre-Certification Bus Training
*4 hours Observation of Certified Driver
* 8 Hours Supervised Driving
*Pass Pre-employment Drug/Alcohol Test
*Pass Expanded Criminal History Background Check

Interested individuals should contact (812) 817-0900 for more information.

post_text:
KEN JOCHEM STATE CHAMPION WELDER!
Pike Central Vocational Welding students through the Patoka Valley Vocational Cooperative swept the top three places at the Skills USA Welding Contest held at J. Everett Light Career Center in Indianapolis on April 16 with Forest Park Senior Ken Jochem placing first; Pike Central Senior Eli Loveland placing second; and Forest Park Senior Travis Jacob placing third. Competing but not placing in the top three were Northeast Dubois Junior Travis Gress and Forest Park Junior Clint Luebbehusen.

We, Rangers of the Southeast Dubois School Corporation, have been asked to compete in the Channel 14 Sunrise School Spirit Challenge to collect canned goods for the Tri-State Food Bank.

We are asking everyone attending the football game against Heritage Hills this Friday to bring canned food items for a chance to win a gift certificate to a local restaurant. Every two canned good items = one raffle ticket. We will also be having competitions among the different schools next week to help collect canned foods.

We look forward to taking the challenge and competing against Heritage Hills, who has collected 3,000 lbs; Jasper, who's collected 6,000 lbs; and Tell City, who's collected 10,000 lbs. Monetary donations will also be accepted and counted as $1=1 canned good.

Thank you for your help and support!

post_text: Ferdinand Day at the Dubois County Museum is THIS Sunday, February 22, from noonto 4:00 p.m. Expect to be entertained, informed and sated. This special day at the museum is thone of several events leading up to Ferdinand’s celebration in June of the town’s 175 anniversary. The FREE event at the Dubois County Museum, located in Jasper, IN, features re­enactors, demonstrations, food sampling, and displays celebrating Ferdinand’s rich heritage.
